    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Does China Deserve Trade Status?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John H Taylor-Dimitri K Simes letter quotes Richard Nixon's argument that economic freedom will inevitably lead to political freedom in China</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire (column, May 18) says President Nixon told him that ''we may have created a Frankenstein'' in United States dealings with China. In ''Beyond Peace,'' finished shortly before his death, Nixon wrote that ''the giant is awake and is beginning to move the world,'' making clear that he saw China's internal dynamics, rather than United States policy, as the force behind the country's emergence as a major power.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire (column, May 18) says President Nixon told him that ''we may have created a Frankenstein'' in United States dealings with China. In ''Beyond Peace,'' finished shortly before his death, Nixon wrote that ''the giant is awake and is beginning to move the world,'' making clear that he saw China's internal dynamics, rather than United States policy, as the force behind the country's emergence as a major power.</p>
        <p>Nixon also argued that ''economic freedom inevitably leads to political freedom. . . . It will happen in China, but only if economic freedom is not suppressed by frightened political dictators or sabotaged by shortsighted U.S. policies cutting back on trade with China because of its human rights abuses.''</p>
        <p>JOHN H. TAYLOR  DIMITRI K. SIMES  Washington, May 19, 2000</p>
        <p>The writers are, respectively, executive director of the Richard Nixon Library &amp; Birthplace Foundation and president of the Nixon Center.</p>
      </block>
